{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d321b74a-3414-4137-b775-8c50a671aef5","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`workload update`** downloads the latest workload versions that match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what realigns everything.\n- **`workload repair`** only *reinstalls* the already-installed versions — it fixes corruption but won't pull in the newer workload packages your updated SDK expects.\n\nSo the typical post-SDK-update fix is:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after that, *then* try `dotnet workload repair` in case something got into a bad state during the update.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"428eb759-db5c-4686-8be9-9c047be2af64","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after an SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a knowledge question, not a code task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, matching them to the current SDK version.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted or incomplete installations, but does **not** update them.\n\nAfter an SDK update, the workloads need to be updated to match the new SDK. `dotnet workload update` is the right choice.","outputTokens":310},"id":"cadae1d0-1fa1-4899-b019-c98b649b1676","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:45:05.377Z","parentId":"5f2c8b74-e301-44f8-b0ed-5af46eb7efb1"}
